04961nam a22007935i 9783035608267DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017sz     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1005663038  a97830356082677 a10.1515/97830356082672doi  a(DE-B1597)465843  a(OCoLC)1004881412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aszcCH 7aARC0150002bisacsh0481pa320qDE-1011 aClouette, Benedict, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aForms of Aid :bArchitectures of Humanitarian Space /cBenedict Clouette, Marlisa Wise. 1aBasel : bBirkhäuser, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. The Spaces of “Humanitarian Space” -- tTYPOLOGIES Wall -- tTYPOLOGIES Tower -- tTYPOLOGIES Shelter -- tTYPOLOGIES Park -- t2. Port-au-Prince and Humanitarian Liberalism -- tTERRITORIES Port-au-Prince, Haiti -- t3. The West Bank and the Humanitarian-Security Complex -- tTERRITORIES West Bank -- tWEST BANK Settlement Growth -- t4. Nairobi and Humanitarian Government -- tTERRITORIES Nairobi, Kenya -- t5. Toward a Politics of Humanitarian Space0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDas Thema Entwicklungszusammenarbeit rückt seit einiger Zeit auch in den Fokus der Ausbildung von Architekten. Doch es gibt bislang kaum Ansätze, die die Arbeit von Architekten und Stadtplaner in diesem Kontext kritisch zu situieren. Das Buch befasst sich mit den architektonischen Folgen humanitärer Aktionen anhand von drei Fallstudien in Port-au-Prince, der Westbank und Nairobi. Aus typologischen und konstruktiven Untersuchungen von zwölf Projekten erarbeiten die Autoren eine differenzierte Position im Diskurs um kurzfristig erstellbare Wohnbauten in Notsituationen. Sie analysieren die weitreichenden Auswirkungen solcher architektonischen Hilfsaktionen und liefern Architekten, Stadtplanern und NGOs nützliche Hinweise für künftige Planungen.  aFor some time now, the subject of cooperation in the context of development aid has featured in the education of architects. However, up to now there have hardly been any attempts to critically place the work of architects and urban designers in this context. The book highlights the architectural consequences of humanitarian actions on the basis of three case studies – in Port-au-Prince, the West Bank, and Nairobi. The authors analyze twelve projects in terms of typology and construction and establish a differentiated position in the discourse on short-term housing for emergency situations. They investigate the far-reaching effects of such architectural aid and supply architects, town planners, and NGOs with useful advice for future planning and design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aARCHITECTURE / Professional Practice.2bisacsh1 aWise, Marlisa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Architecture and Design 2017z9783110547719oZDB-23-DAD08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z97831106252640 cprintz978303561021540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978303560826740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783035608267423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783035608267.jpg  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-071954-3  DG Plus eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA